	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
	
			<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
			Topic: direction <BR>
<BR>
Saw a lot of talk on using sense heading in this thread. I don't use it and don't think it's very worthwhile, especially with the pain in the ass of having to be hitting it all the time to get it better. <BR>
<BR>
My experience on this has been this, in the early days of your character your sense heading doesnt work at all. As a result, with my first guy, I ended up learning landmarks in Everfrost and the tundra. As a result I ended up knowing the land well. You know that a river runs this or that way, a mountain range is on your southern border, a rock with ice on it is at a certain juncture, the druid at the stones faces east, the clouds go west, etc. THis is a much better to know your way around then using that damn sense heading button. Look at it this way, you are chasing some monsters around in a zone, boom, you are in some area you dont know, and your sense heading says you are facing north. Are you facing north on the east side of the zone or the west? If youre sense heaing skills stinks, which it probably does, you don't know, and have to hit it twenty more times after rotating 45 degrees. Screw it. Learn the land. <BR>
<BR>
If you're in a new zone, and don't know the land, do a copper run. Stick in an area, kill everything that is there, help newbies, and, after all, a coin is a coin. ANd in the process you will learn the land. If you're in a new higher level zone then stay in a limited area and keep killing the respawns until you know the land there and then venture further. <BR>
<BR>
Just my take. <BR>
<BR>
Caanite
			</font>
	
		</td>
	</tr>
	
