		<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
	
			<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
			Sorry to nitpick on you, Cracken, but that was the Spartans who held the way in Thermopylae, not the Athenians.  Only three hundred of them, too, against thousands of Persians.  Its likely they would have held out quite a lot longer, in fact, had not a renegade Greek shown the Persians a back route through the cliffside.<BR>
<BR>
But your point is well taken.  Its definitely very irritatating that pcs can't occupy the same space, but the monsters can.  It certainly would make fighting trains a lot easier if you had to face them at only two at a time.  It would also make it quite a lot easier to keep a MoB (what does that stand for, anyway?) from running if you could box it in.<BR>
<BR>
And speaking of running, sometimes it is *extremely* difficult to prevent a monster from getting away.  There's at least one door in BB that pcs can't open, for example, and the gnolls unerringly run through it.  Also, the computer is better at navigating than any but the best players.  Often, when a critter runs, it brings back help, hence the train begins.  I once ended up fighting no less than 6 gnoll guardsmen in the spike pit.<BR>
<BR>
As far as not training to the zone goes, where else is one supposed to go?  Because of the computer's navigation, you can't lose something unless you've got SoW or can take a big fall (and even then you often don't lose them.)  Zoning is generally the only way to stay alive.
			</font>
	
		</td>
